{"title_page": "Smash (TV series)", "text_new": "{{For|the 1990 Swedish comedy miniseries|Smash (miniseries)}}\n{{short description|2012 American television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| genre                = [[Jukebox musical]]<br />[[Drama]]\n| show_name            = Smash\n| image                = [[File:Smash Title Card.jpg|250px]]\n| caption              =\n| show_name_2          =\n| creator              = [[Theresa Rebeck]]\n| developer            = [[Robert Greenblatt]] (uncredited)\n| starring             = {{Plain list|\n*[[Debra Messing]]\n*[[Jack Davenport]]\n*[[Katharine McPhee]]\n*[[Christian Borle]]\n*[[Megan Hilty]]\n*[[Anjelica Huston]]\n*[[Leslie Odom old\n.]]\n*[[Jeremy Jordan (actor, born 1984)|Jeremy Jordan]]\n*[[Krysta Rodriguez]]\n*[[Andy Mientus]]\n*[[Raza Jaffrey]]\n*[[Brian d'Arcy James]]\n*Jaime Cepero\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Marc Shaiman]]\n| opentheme            = \"5, 6, 7, 8\" (Season 2)\n| endtheme             =\n| composer             = {{Plain list|\n*[[Marc Shaiman]]\n*[[Scott Wittman]]\n*[[Chris Bacon (composer)|Chris Bacon]] <small>(score, episodes 7\u201332)</small>\n}}\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 2\n| num_episodes         = 32\n| list_episodes        = List of Smash episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plain list|\n*[[Craig Zadan]]\n*[[Neil Meron]]\n*Darryl Frank\n*Justin Falvey\n*[[Marc Shaiman]]\n*[[Scott Wittman]]\n*[[Steven Spielberg]]\n*[[Theresa Rebeck]]\n*[[David Marshall Grant]]\n*[[Joshua Safran]]\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plain list|\n*[[Jordon Nardino]]\n*Jim Chory\n}}\n| editor               = {{Plain list|\n*Andy Weisblum <small>(pilot only)</small>\n*Bill Henry\n*Camilla Toniolo\n*Allyson Johnson\n}}\n| location             = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| cinematography       = {{Plain list|\n*[[Shelly Johnson (cinematographer)|Shelly Johnson]] <small>(pilot only)</small>\n*[[M. David Mullen]]\n}}\n| camera               =\n| runtime              = 40\u201345 minutes\n| company              = {{Plain list|\n*Madwoman in the Attic, Inc.<br>(2012)<br>(season 1)\n*[[DreamWorks Television]]\n*[[Universal Television]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]]\n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format         =\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2012|2|6}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2013|05|26}}\n| website              = http://www.nbc.com/smash/\n| website_title        = Official website\n| production_website   =\n| related              =\n}}\n\n'''''Smash''''' is an American [[Musical film|musical]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] television series created by playwright [[Theresa Rebeck]] and developed by [[Robert Greenblatt]] for [[NBC]]. [[Steven Spielberg]] served as one of the executive producers. The series was broadcast in the US by NBC and produced by [[DreamWorks Television]] and [[Universal Television]]. The series revolves around a fictional [[New York City]] theater community and specifically the creation of a new [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] musical. It features a large ensemble cast, led by [[Debra Messing]], [[Jack Davenport]], [[Katharine McPhee]], [[Christian Borle]], [[Megan Hilty]], and [[Anjelica Huston]].\n\nThe show debuted on February 6, 2012, and its first season ended on May 14, 2012. Its second season premiered on February 5, 2013, and ended on May 26, 2013. NBC announced a change in their lineup in March 2013 and moved the show to Saturdays starting April 6, 2013.<ref name=\"SmashSatTVbtN\">{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title=NBC Announces 'Smash' Saturday Burn-Off, Shuffles 'Go On' and 'The New Normal' Finales & Moves 'Ready for Love' Into Post-Voice Tuesday Slot|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/03/13/nbc-announces-smash-saturday-burn-off-shuffles-go-on-and-the-new-normal-finales-moves-ready-for-love-into-post-voice-tuesday-slot/173353/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=March 13, 2013|date=March 13, 2013}}</ref> The series was cancelled on May 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title='Smash' Officially Canceled by NBC After Two Seasons|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/05/10/smash-officially-canceled/182220/|publisher=TVbytheNumbers|accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/nbc-cancels-smash-after-two-seasons/ |title=NBC Cancels 'Smash' After Two Seasons |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |work=[[TV Line]] |date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> Second-season executive producer-show runner [[Josh Safran]] said the final episode of season two worked as a series finale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/03/15/smash-season-2-series-finale-spoilers/ |title=Exclusive: Smash Boss 'Saddened' By Saturday Move, Says Season Is Building to Series Finale |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |work=[[TV Line]] |date=March 15, 2013|accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe series, especially the pilot episode, enjoyed critical success. The first season received the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Choreography]] among four nominations. The series was also nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy and a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Song Written for Visual Media (\"[[Let Me Be Your Star]]\").\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Smash episodes}}\n{{:List of Smash episodes}}\nThe show revolves around a group of characters creating new [[Broadway musical]]s, where everyone must balance their often chaotic personal life with the all-consuming demands of life in the theater. The series features original music by composers [[Marc Shaiman]] and [[Scott Wittman]].\n\n===Season 1 (2012)===\n{{main|Smash (season 1)}}\nJulia Houston ([[Debra Messing]]) and Tom Levitt ([[Christian Borle]]), a Broadway writing team, came up with the idea of a new musical based on the life of [[Marilyn Monroe]] titled ''[[Bombshell (musical)|Bombshell]]''. Producer Eileen Rand ([[Anjelica Huston]]), in the midst of divorce proceedings from her philandering husband, jumps on board and brings with her Derek Wills ([[Jack Davenport]]), a difficult but brilliant director. Ivy Lynn ([[Megan Hilty]]) is initially cast as Marilyn, but is forced to deal with competition from the talented, yet naive ensemble member Karen Cartwright ([[Katharine McPhee]]). Julia's former lover Michael Swift ([[Will Chase]]) is initially cast in the role of [[Joe DiMaggio]]. However, when Julia and Michael's reunion causes serious trouble in her marriage to Frank ([[Brian d'Arcy James]]), the decision is made to fire Michael. The role of Marilyn is recast with film star Rebecca Duvall ([[Uma Thurman]]), leaving Ivy devastated. After a somewhat disastrous out-of-town opening in Boston, Rebecca has fallen sick due to a peanut allergy and the actor playing Joe departs the production for a better gig. Derek subsequently casts Karen in the role of Marilyn and Michael is reinstated as Joe. Karen discovers Ivy has slept with her fianc\u00e9 Dev ([[Raza Jaffrey]]), while Eileen finds out that her assistant Ellis (Jaime Cepero) was the one who poisoned Rebecca and fires him. Karen gets through her debut and the season ends with the closing number being applauded by the audience.\n\n===Season 2 (2013)===\n{{main|Smash (season 2)}}\nAs ''[[Bombshell (musical)|Bombshell]]'' works to open on Broadway in New York City, the show runs into legal and creative troubles which threaten its future.  Meanwhile, the cast and crew (featured in Season 1) attempt to find work. Karen meets two aspiring friends and partners (Kyle, a stage writer played by Andy Mientus, and Jimmy, a composer played by [[Jeremy Jordan (actor, born 1984)|Jeremy Jordan]]) and tries to get their work noticed, especially by Derek. Derek works with Broadway star Veronica Moore ([[Jennifer Hudson]]), who becomes friends with Karen. Ivy gets the lead in ''Liaisons'', a show based on the play ''[[Les liaisons dangereuses (play)|Les Liaisons Dangereuses]]''. ''[[Bombshell (musical)|Bombshell]]'' needs work in order to open on Broadway. First, Peter Gillman ([[Daniel Sunjata]]), a [[dramaturg]] with whom Julia had a rocky relationship is hired in order to help re-write the show. Second, Jerry ([[Michael Cristofer]]) replaces Eileen as the show's producer after she had to step down when the federal authorities found out (through Jerry's orchestration) that she had financed ''Bombshell'' with illegal money. Jimmy and Kyle's show, called ''[[Hit List (musical)|Hit List]]'', eventually goes to the New York Fringe Festival and then they meet a producer for an off-broadway theater called Manhattan Theatre Workshop. Karen quits ''Bombshell'' to be in ''Hit List'' because she has to choose one of them. Ivy takes Karen's role as Marilyn Monroe in ''Bombshell''. ''Hit List'' starts rehearsals. Karen and Jimmy's relationship starts to develop but may cause some disturbance in the work place with Derek's secret feelings for Karen. ''Hit List'' goes to Broadway produced by Jerry and ''Bombshell'' and ''Hit List'' go face to face at the [[Tony Awards]]. ''Hit List'' wins 7 Tonys, which is more than ''Bombshell'', however ''Bombshell'' wins Best Musical and Best Actress (Ivy Lynn) in a Leading Role.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{main|Characters of Smash}}\n* [[Debra Messing]] as Julia Houston,<ref name=\"smashbios\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcumv.com/mediavillage/networks/nbcentertainment/smash/biographies |title=Smash Biographies |publisher=NBCUniversal Media Village |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205003041/http://www.nbcumv.com/mediavillage/networks/nbcentertainment/smash/biographies |archivedate=February 5, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> a successful Broadway lyricist and the musical's co-writer. She is married with a son, but had an affair with Michael Swift, who played Joe DiMaggio in the initial ''Marilyn'' workshop. Houston is based on creator Theresa Rebeck.<ref name=\"THR1\" />\n* [[Jack Davenport]] as Derek Wills,<ref name=\"smashbios\"/> the director of the musical, who will stop at nothing to make the show a success. He has an on-and-off relationship with ''Marilyn'' workshop star Ivy Lynn, though he has also shown interest in Karen Cartwright and had a physical relationship with Rebecca Duvall during the Boston preview before she left the show.\n* [[Katharine McPhee]] as Karen Cartwright,<ref name=\"smashbios\"/> an [[Ingenue (stock character)|ingenue]] from [[Iowa]], who lands a successful audition and becomes a serious contender for the role of Monroe. Somewhat new to show business, her naivet\u00e9 is generally scorned by her peers, though her talent is rarely called into question. She played Marilyn for the Boston preview, when Rebecca Duvall left. In season 2, she helps ''Hit List'' get started and plays Amanda/Nina after she quits Bombshell.\n* [[Christian Borle]] as Tom Levitt,<ref name=\"smashbios\"/> a theatrical composer and Julia's longtime songwriting partner. He and Derek Wills have an acrimonious relationship stemming from a business fallout 11 years ago. Tom briefly dates a Republican lawyer but later becomes attracted to Sam Strickland, a dancer in the ensemble of ''Bombshell''.\n* [[Megan Hilty]] as Ivy Lynn,<ref name=\"smashbios\"/> a seasoned performer who, at the beginning of the series, is working in the ensemble of ''Heaven On Earth'', another Broadway musical that Tom and Julia wrote. Ivy is favored by nearly everyone on board with the production to play Marilyn Monroe, but after the workshop flops, she is replaced by Rebecca Duvall. Throughout the show, she is in an on-and-off relationship with the ''Bombshell'' director Derek Wills and finds herself constantly competing with Karen in many different situations, eventually losing the role of Marilyn to her for the Boston preview.\n* [[Anjelica Huston]] as Eileen Rand,<ref name=\"smashbios\"/> the musical's tenacious producer, who is dealing with divorce proceedings from her husband, Jerry, which could threaten the musical and forces her to think outside the box in securing funds for the show.  A running gag throughout the series is Eileen throwing drinks into Jerry's face.\n* [[Jeremy Jordan (actor, born 1984)|Jeremy Jordan]] as Jimmy Collins (Season 2), a working-class man from Brooklyn who is on the brink of self-destruction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/05/21/smash-season-2-casting-new-series-regulars/|title=Exclusive: ''Smash'' Shakes Up Cast, Adding Three New Regulars for Season 2|first=Matt Webb|last=Mitovich|publisher=TVLine|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=June 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/06/14/smash-jeremy-jordan/|title=''Smash'' Exclusive: ''Newsies'' Star Jeremy Jordan Joins Season 2 Cast as a Series Regular|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|publisher=TVLine|date=June 14, 2012|accessdate=June 14, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Leslie Odom, Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/leslie-odom-jr-krysta-rodriguez-added-to-smash-cast/|title=Leslie Odom Jr., Krysta Rodriguez Added To 'Smash' Cast|first=The |last=Deadline Team|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 6, 2012|accessdate=June 6, 2012}}</ref> as Sam Strickland (regular Season 2, recurring Season 1), an ensemble member, a good friend of Ivy who is gay and very much into sports. Due to their mutual friendship with Ivy, he forms a connection with Tom.\n* [[Andy Mientus]] as Kyle Bishop (Season 2), a poor kid from Brooklyn with dreams of writing for Broadway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/06/26/smash-season-2-andy-mientus/|title=Exclusive: ''Smash'' Season 2 Casting Exclusive: Will the New Guy Have the Write Stuff?|first=Matt Webb|last=Mitovich|publisher=TVLine|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref> He is the writer of the book of ''Hit List.''\n* [[Krysta Rodriguez]] as Ana Vargas (Season 2), Karen's new roommate who is looking for her big break.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2012/07/06/smash-krysta-rodriguez-season-2/ |title=''Smash'' Scoop: Meet Karen's Spunky New [Spoiler] |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |publisher=TVLine |date=July 6, 2012|accessdate=July 6, 2012}}</ref>\n* Jaime Cepero as Ellis Boyd (Season 1),<ref name=\"smashbios\"/><ref name=\"season2cast\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thecallboard.com/042011/exclusive-interview-with-nbcs-jaime-cepero-getting-smashed |title=<nowiki>Exclusive interview with NBC's Jaime Cepero [getting smashed</nowiki><nowiki>]</nowiki> |first=Peter |last=Dagger |publisher=The Callboard |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=January 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129153523/http://thecallboard.com/042011/exclusive-interview-with-nbcs-jaime-cepero-getting-smashed |archivedate=January 29, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Tom's and later Eileen's conniving personal assistant who is attempting to receive credit for ''Bombshell'' and make his way as a show producer. As the first season continues, Ellis, convinced his suggestion of Marilyn created the show, takes more steps to be recognized as a producer, including giving Rebecca a drink mixed with peanuts, which she is allergic to, in order to remove her as the star. He boasts of this to Eileen as proof of his skills but she responds by firing him.\n* [[Raza Jaffrey]] as Dev Sundaram (Season 1),<ref name=\"smashbios\"/><ref name=\"season2cast\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/smash_shocker_which_stars_were_just/318281 |title=''Smash'' Shocker! Which Stars Were Just Axed From Season Two? |first=Jenna|last=Mullins|publisher=E! Online|date=May 22, 2012|accessdate=May 28, 2012}}</ref> Karen's live-in boyfriend, who works in the office of the New York City mayor's [[press secretary]] who ultimately forces her to choose between their relationship or her career. He proposes marriage but when Karen is unsure, a despondent and intoxicated Dev sleeps with Ivy. Upon realizing who Dev is, Ivy tells Karen of their encounter and an angry Karen breaks up with Dev.\n* [[Brian d'Arcy James]] as Frank Houston (regular Season 1, guest Season 2),<ref name=\"smashbios\"/><ref name=\"season2cast\"/> Julia's husband and a high-school chemistry teacher, who wishes that Julia would spend more time at home. He was upset when she confessed to her affair with Michael Swift and more so when he confronted Swift and learned Julia had cheated on him earlier in the marriage. They eventually separated in the season 2 premiere. In the final episode of the program Julia makes good with Frank and both of them go easy on their divorce proceedings. James was credited as guest star in the pilot, but was promoted to regular from episode 2. He made guest appearances in the second-season premiere and the series finale.\n\n==Development and production==\n\n===Conception===\nDevelopment began in 2009 at [[Showtime (TV channel)|Showtime]] by then-Showtime entertainment president [[Robert Greenblatt]] and [[Steven Spielberg]], from an idea by Spielberg, who had been working on the concept for years;<ref name=showspielteam>{{cite news | url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118008994 | title = Showtime, Spielberg team on series | last = Littleton | first = Cynthia |date = September 22, 2009 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | accessdate = June 10, 2011 }}</ref> Greenblatt, described as a \"devoted theater geek\", had also produced a short-lived [[9 to 5 (musical)|musical adaptation]] of the film ''[[9 to 5 (film)|9 to 5]]'' in 2009.<ref name=\"Buzzfeed story\">{{cite news|last=Aurthur|first=Kate|title=How 'Smash' Became TV's Biggest Train Wreck|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/kateaurthur/how-smash-became-tvs-biggest-train-wreck|newspaper=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=January 30, 2013|accessdate=March 22, 2013}}</ref> The original concept was that each season would follow the production of a new musical; if any of them were \"stage-worthy\", Spielberg would make them into actual Broadway musicals.<ref name=\"concept\">{{cite web|last=Green |first=Jesse |url=https://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/smash-2012-1/index1.html |title=Will 'Smash' on NBC Be a Success? |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=January 2, 2012 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> The series was inspired by ''[[The West Wing (TV series)|The West Wing]]'' and ''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs, Downstairs]]'' as role models for successful TV dramas. [[Garson Kanin]]'s novel ''[[Smash (novel)|Smash]]'' (New York: Viking, 1980) provided the title and setting, although the plots have little in common.<ref name=\"concept\"/>\n\nGreenblatt then brought the project with him to [[NBC]] when he was made NBC Entertainment president in January 2011. [[Theresa Rebeck]] wrote the pilot script and is series creator.<ref name=\"concept\"/> Executive producers [[Craig Zadan]] and [[Neil Meron]] suggested Rebeck for the series to Spielberg and Greenblatt.<ref name=\"concept\"/> NBC ordered production of a pilot in January 2011 for the [[2011\u201312 United States network television schedule|2011\u201312 television season]].<ref name=pilotordered>{{cite news | url = https://www.deadline.com/2011/01/nbc-picks-up-2-pilots-including-hourlong-musical-from-steven-spielberg/ | title = NBC Orders Steven Spielberg Musical Pilot | last = Andreeva | first = Nellie |date = January 21, 2011 | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | accessdate = June 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[Michael Mayer (director)|Michael Mayer]] directed the pilot episode, with Spielberg serving as an executive producer.<ref name=nbcups>{{cite news | url = https://www.deadline.com/2011/05/nbc-unveils-2011-12-primetime-schedule/ | title = NBC Unveils 2011\u20132012 Primetime Schedule | last = Andreeva | first = Nellie |date = May 15, 2011 | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | accessdate = June 10, 2011 }}</ref> It has been reported that the pilot cost $7.5&nbsp;million to produce.<ref name=\"concept\"/><ref name=pilotcost>{{cite news | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/heard-inside-upfront-parties-presentations-190389 | title = Heard Inside the Upfront Parties and Presentations | last = Masters | first = Kim | last2 = Guthries | first2 = Marisa |date = May 20, 2011 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | accessdate = June 10, 2011 }}</ref> On May 11, 2011, NBC picked the project up to series. When the network announced its 2011\u201312 schedule on May 15, 2011, the series was slated to premiere in mid-season.<ref name=nbcups/> NBC opted to hold the show for mid-season in order to pair it up with the hit reality show ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' on Monday nights.<ref name=pairing>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/17/business/media/17adco.html | title = For Fox and NBC, Let the Singing Begin | last = Carter | first = Bill | last2=Stelter | first2= Brian |date = May 16, 2011 | work = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = June 10, 2011 }}</ref> On August 1, 2011, it was announced by the press that show's series premiere date would be February 6, 2012, the night after [[Super Bowl XLVI]], with heavy promotion through early winter on many of the network's properties before the premiere.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/153252-Smash-Drama-Series-Will-Launch-in-February-2012-With-Christian-Borle-Megan-Hilty-Debra-Messing |title=\"Smash\" Drama Series Will Launch in February 2012 With Christian Borle, Megan Hilty, Debra Messing |work=Playbill |date=August 1, 2011 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |last1=Gans |first1=Andrew |last2=Jones |first2=Kenneth |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111061728/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/153252-Smash-Drama-Series-Will-Launch-in-February-2012-With-Christian-Borle-Megan-Hilty-Debra-Messing |archivedate=January 11, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Valby |first=Karen |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/08/01/voice-premiere-date/ |title=NBC announces 'The Voice' return date |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> At the NBC Press Tour, Greenblatt announced that ''Smash'' would have 15 episodes produced for the first season to coincide with ''The Voice''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/press-tour-nbc-boss-on-community-parks-and-recreation-chuck-and-more|title=Press tour: NBC boss on 'Community,' 'Parks and Recreation,' 'Chuck' and more|first=Alan|last=Sepinwall|publisher=HitFix|date=August 1, 2011|accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Crew===\nThe series is a production of [[Universal Television]] in association with [[DreamWorks Television|DreamWorks]].<ref name=nbcups/> [[Theresa Rebeck]] is the creator of the series as well as the writer of the pilot episode<ref name=nbcups/> and five episodes of the first season, including the season finale. The series has a large number of executive producers including [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Craig Zadan]], [[Neil Meron]], [[David Marshall Grant]], Rebeck, Darryl Frank and Justin Falvey.<ref name=nbcups/> [[Marc Shaiman]] and [[Scott Wittman]] serve as the composers and executive producers.<ref name=nbcups/> In March 2012, Rebeck stepped down as showrunner of the musical drama.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title='Smash' Creator Theresa Rebeck To Depart |url=https://www.deadline.com/tag/theresa-rebeck/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=April 25, 2012 |date=March 22, 2012}}</ref> On April 24, 2012, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' reported that ''[[Gossip Girl]]'' executive producer [[Joshua Safran]] would take the lead for the second season while Rebeck would remain a writer and an executive producer.<ref name=\"THR1\">{{cite news |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |title='Smash' Taps 'Gossip Girl's' Josh Safran as New Showrunner |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/smash-gossip-girl-josh-safran-showrunner-315983 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=April 25, 2012|date=April 24, 2012}}</ref> However, on May 2, 2012, Rebeck stated in an interview that she would not be returning to the show in any capacity.<ref>{{cite web |last=Siegler |first=Mara |title=Showrunner Theresa Rebeck on Smash: 'I'm Moving On' |url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/05/theresa-rebeck-on-smash-im-moving-on.html |publisher=Vulture.com |accessdate=May 21, 2012|date=May 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nMany of those behind ''Smash'' began the series with high hopes. Rebeck was a large part of that. As one early hire later described her to ''[[BuzzFeed]]'': \"She was this kick-ass woman [[showrunner]] who wasn't taking shit from the network. Someone who had a very clear vision who was going to stand up to the network. They were all good things in the beginning.\"<ref name=\"Buzzfeed story\" />\n\nDespite her experience writing and producing in television, Rebeck had never been a showrunner, responsible for the day-to-day operations of a series, before. [[David Marshall Grant]], a [[playwright]] and actor who had served in that capacity during ''[[Brothers & Sisters (2006 TV series)|Brothers & Sisters]]''' final seasons, was hired as [[executive producer]] to help her with it. Rebeck was reportedly resentful, and worried that she was being [[setting up to fail|set up to fail]] and Grant positioned to replace her. Very quickly she began shutting him out of key decisions.<ref name=\"Buzzfeed story\" />\n\nRebeck also decided she would not run a \"writers' room,\" i.e., a regular meeting with the entire writing staff to discuss and perfect episodes and plotlines. \"[They] really are not my thing, because I can only stand being in a room with people so many hours a day,\" she told ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''. \"And I feel like early drafts should be speedy because everyone changes their mind, so why spend a lot of time up front parsing sentences?\"<ref name=\"NY mag preview story\">{{cite news|last=Green|first=Jesse|title=A House of Mirrors Called 'Smash'|url=https://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/smash-2012-1/index2.html|newspaper=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=December 26, 2011|accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref>  Instead she would follow the example of showrunners like [[Matthew Weiner]] and [[Aaron Sorkin]] and have writers submit a first draft, which she then revised.<ref name=\"Buzzfeed story\" />\n\nVery quickly, the writers recalled, the show became a \"dictatorship.\" Rebeck's opinion was the only one that mattered. She insisted on writing the second and third episodes herself, and writers said that the drop in quality was evident during pre-air screenings. During this time Rebeck was often fighting with Spielberg, who wanted Hilty, Greenblatt, or Grant replaced. As a result of these distractions, plotlines like Julia's adoption dilemma (mirroring Rebeck's real life) began to assume unusual prominence, and along with them secondary characters like Leo and Ellis became almost main characters\u2014the latter because Spielberg reportedly liked him.<ref name=\"Buzzfeed story\" />\n\nSince the writers never met as a group, they found that finished episodes often repeated the same character moments instead of advancing those characters, and that strange out-of-context moments, usually musical numbers set away from the stage, had been inserted. They were particularly frustrated in trying to write for Julia, whom Rebeck had based on herself and consequently would not allow to have any difficulties. Later in the season, they were hoping that Greenblatt would win some of their fights. \"You know it's bad when ''our last hope was the network'',\" one told ''BuzzFeed''. However, many of them said the show's own problems were not entirely Rebeck's fault, since Greenblatt also intervened in things like costume design and Spielberg was not informed of the conflicts until near the end.<ref name=\"Buzzfeed story\" />\n\nAfter she left the show, Rebeck, who, citing confidentiality requirements, did not respond to the ''BuzzFeed'' story at first other than to say she \"was treated quite badly\",<ref name=\"Buzzfeed story\" /> spoke at some length to ''[[The New York Observer]]'' about ''Smash'':\n{{quote|One of the points of contention last year was that the network thinks they have the right to say to the writer of the show, \"We don't want her to do this. We want her to do this ... And I would sometimes say back to them, \"She would never do that.\" And they'd look at me like I was crazy, and I'd be like, \"Nope, it's not crazy, it's just who the character is.\" You have to respect who the character is. It has its own internal truth and you can't betray that. And if you don't betray that, it will not betray you. There is this sort of sense that if you don't fuck with the muse\u2014if you don't fuck with the muse, the muse will stand by you ...  It turns into bigger questions about power and art, power and storytelling. Is power itself bigger than storytelling? And I would say no.<ref name=\"NY Observer Rebeck interview\">{{cite news|last=D'Addario|first=Daniel|title=Rebeck Redux: Smushed by ''Smash'', Playwright Bounces Back With Katie Holmes-Starring Play|url=http://observer.com/2012/11/rebeck-redux-smushed-by-smash-playwright-bounces-back-with-katie-holmes-starring-play/?show=all|newspaper=[[The New York Observer]]|date=November 27, 2012|accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nFollowing the show's cancellation, Kate Aurthur, the writer of the ''BuzzFeed'' story, reposted an email exchange she had with Rebeck. Pointing to the show's decline in ratings during its second season, Rebeck asked, \"If in fact [I] was the problem with [the show], wouldn't things have gotten better\u2014rather than dramatically worse\u2014once [I] left?\" She accused Aurthur of relying on a single unnamed source and asked that the story, which she called \"wildly untrue\", be taken down.<ref name=\"BuzzFeed Rebeck exchange post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/kateaurthur/smash-creator-theresa-rebeck-emailed-me|last=Aurthur|first=Kate|title=\"Smash\" Creator Theresa Rebeck Emailed Me|publisher=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=April 30, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|List of songs in Smash}}\nNBC announced on June 9, 2011, that they had signed a deal with [[Columbia Records]] for a soundtrack of the series. The deal gives Columbia worldwide digital and physical rights to the first season, with options to subsequent seasons. The deal includes both original songs written for the series and any covers of songs featured on the show.<ref name=crtwnbc>{{cite news | url = https://www.deadline.com/2011/06/columbia-records-teams-with-nbc-for-smash-music-albums-inks-solo-recording-deal-with-co-star-kathatine-mcphee/ | title = Columbia Records Teams With NBC For 'Smash' Music Albums, Inks Solo Recording Deal With Co-Star Katharine McPhee | last = Andreeva | first = Nellie |date = June 9, 2011 | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | accessdate = June 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe series soundtrack for Season 1, ''[[The Music of Smash]]'',  was released on May 1, 2012.<ref name=crtwnbc /><ref>{{cite news | url = http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/04/02/smash-soundtrack-set-for-release-on-may-1/127062/ | title = 'Smash' Soundtrack Set for Release on May 1 | last = Bibel | first = Sara |date = April 2, 2012 | publisher = [[TV by the Numbers]] | accessdate = April 2, 2012 }}</ref> The album debuted on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at #9 with 40,000 copies sold in its first week.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/05/09/carrie-underwood-blown-away-norah-jones-chart/ | title = Album Sales: Carrie Underwood rules supreme, Norah Jones takes the second-place spot | last = Smith | first = Grady |date = May 9, 2012 | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate = May 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA ''[[Bombshell (Smash album)|Bombshell]]'' [[cast recording]], featuring original songs from the first and second season of the show, was released on February 12, 2013, selling 16,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grammy sales boost Carrie Underwood above 'Idol' pack|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/idolchatter/2013/02/20/carrie-underwood-grammy-sales-boost/1932473/|last=Mansfield|first=Brian|work=Idol Chatter|publisher=USAToday|date=February 20, 2013|accessdate=February 20, 2013}}</ref> It contains all 22 songs written for the fictional ''Bombshell'' musical and features lead vocals by [[Katharine McPhee]] (Karen Cartwright) and [[Megan Hilty]] (Ivy Lynn) as Marilyn Monroe.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/07/smash-bombshell-soundtrack_n_2423945.html |newspaper=The Huffington Post |date=January 6, 2013 |title='Smash': 'Bombshell' Soundtrack Heading to Stores |accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to songs by Marc Shaiman and Scott Wittman, the show's second season featured songs by up-and-coming composers [[Drew Gasparini]], [[Joe Iconis]], and writing duo [[Pasek and Paul|Benj Pasek & Justin Paul]].\n\nSeveral songs were written and performed for the series' season two fictional musical, ''[[Hit List (musical)|Hit List]]''. On October 15, 2013, it was announced that ''Hit List'' would be staged in concert format at [[54 Below]] on December 9. ''Smash'' stars Jeremy Jordan, Andy Mientus and Krysta Rodriguez were scheduled to perform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/172361/smash-fans-rejoice-hit-list-to-debut-at-54-below-starring-jeremy-jordan-krysta-rodriguez-andy-mientus/|title=Smash Fans, Rejoice! Hit List to Debut at 54 Below, Starring Jeremy Jordan, Krysta Rodriguez & Andy Mientus|work=Broadway.com|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref> Because of demand for tickets, an additional performance was scheduled for December 8.<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/183965-54-Below-Adds-Dec-8-Hit-List-Concert-Based-on-Fictional-Smash-Musical 54 Below Adds Dec. 8 ''Hit List'' Concert, Based on Fictional \"Smash\" Musical] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105045528/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/183965-54-Below-Adds-Dec-8-Hit-List-Concert-Based-on-Fictional-Smash-Musical |date=November 5, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===''Bombshell'' musical numbers===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n; Act I\n* \"[[Let Me Be Your Star]]\" \u2013 [[Marilyn Monroe|Norma Jeane Mortenson]]\n* \"At Your Feet\" \u2013 Gladys, young Norma Jeane, Tourists and Hollywood Citizens\n* \"[[Never Give All the Heart]]\" \u2013 Norma Jeane\n* \"[[The 20th Century Fox Mambo]]\" \u2013 Marilyn Monroe and [[Twentieth Century Fox]] Studio Staff\n* \"[[The National Pastime]]\" \u2013 Marilyn and New York Yankees\n* \"[[History Is Made at Night (song)|History is Made at Night]]\" \u2013 Marilyn, [[Joe DiMaggio]] and Lovers\n* \"[[I Never Met a Wolf Who Didn't Love to Howl]]\" \u2013 Marilyn and Troops\n* \"[[Mr. & Mrs. Smith (song)|Mr. & Mrs. Smith]]\" \u2013 Marilyn and Joe DiMaggio\n* \"[[Don't Say Yes Until I Finish Talking]]\" \u2013 [[Darryl F. Zanuck]] and Studio Executives\n* \"Smash!\" \u2013 Aspiring Actresses\n* \"[[On Lexington & 52nd Street]]\" \u2013 Joe DiMaggio, Marilyn, Reporter and New York Citizens\n* \"Cut, Print...Moving On\" \u2013 Marilyn and Studio Staff\n\n{{col-2}}\n; Act II\n* \"Public Relations\" \u2013 Marilyn and Press\n* \"[[Dig Deep]]\" \u2013 Marilyn, [[Lee Strasberg]] and Students\n* \"[[Second Hand White Baby Grand]]\" \u2013 Marilyn\n* \"They Just Keep Moving the Line\" \u2013 Marilyn\n* \"[[Let's Be Bad (song)|Let's Be Bad]]\" \u2013 Marilyn and the cast of ''[[Some Like It Hot]]''\n* \"The Right Regrets\" \u2013 [[Arthur Miller]]\n* \"Our Little Secret\" \u2013 [[John F. Kennedy]] and Marilyn\n* \"Hang the Moon\" \u2013 Gladys and Marilyn\n* \"[[Don't Forget Me (Smash song)|Don't Forget Me]]\" \u2013 Marilyn\n{{col-end}}\n\n===''Hit List'' musical numbers===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n; Act I\n* \"Broadway Here I Come (Pre-reprise)\" \u2014 The Diva\n* \"[[Rewrite This Story]]\" \u2014 Amanda and Jesse\n* \"Good for You\" \u2014 Amanda\n* \"Broadway Here I Come!\" \u2014 Amanda\n* \"The Love I Meant to Say\" \u2014 Jesse\n* \"Reach for Me\" \u2014 The Diva\n* \"Original\" \u2014 Amanda\n* \"The Love I Meant To Say (Reprise)\" \u2014 Amanda (as \"Nina\")\n* \"[[I Heard Your Voice In a Dream]]\" \u2014 Jesse\n* \"Don't Let Me Know\" \u2014 Amanda (as \"Nina\") and Jesse\n* \"Pretender\" \u2014 Amanda (as \"Nina\")\n* \"I'm Not Sorry\" \u2014 Amanda (as \"Nina\") and The Diva\n* \"I Heard Your Voice In a Dream (Reprise)\" \u2014 Jesse\n* \"Caught In the Storm\" \u2014 Jesse\n\n{{col-2}}\n; Act II\n* \"[TBD Coming Home Song]\" \u2014 The Diva (as \"Sara Smith\")\n* \"Good for You\" \u2014 Amanda (as \"Nina\")\n* \"[[Heart Shaped Wreckage]]\" \u2014 Amanda and Jesse\n* \"Broadway Here I Come (Reprise)\" \u2014 Amanda\n* \"The Love I Meant to Say (Reprise)\" \u2014 Jesse\n* \"The Goodbye Song\" \u2014 Jesse, Amanda, The Diva and Ensemble<ref>[https://www.vulture.com/2013/05/smash-hit-list-plot-revealed.html The Unspoken Full Plot for ''Smash''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 'Hit List' Musical Is Revealed]</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Original Broadway production===\n\nDuring production of the show, executive producer Craig Zadan said: \"We stand on the set, watch the ''Bombshell'' numbers and say, \"Wouldn't this be great on Broadway? And so far that's where we've left it. Our priority now is producing a great TV show\".<ref>http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/smash-producers-musical-hit-broadway-article-1.1234794</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, following the sold-out performance at the Minskoff Theatre, it was announced that ''Bombshell'' would head to the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] stage. The executive producers of ''Smash'' and the ''Bombshell'' concert [[Neil Meron]] and [[Craig Zadan]] are set to executive produce the Broadway production. No timeline for the show has been announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/smash-musical-bombshell-headed-to-the-stage-351824|title=\"Smash\" Musical Bombshell Headed to the Stage|work=Playbill|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe pilot of ''Smash'' received positive reviews from television critics, but the critical response was less positive as the season progressed.\n\nReview aggregator ''[[Metacritic]]'', which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 of reviews from mainstream critics, calculated a score of 79 based on 32 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/smash|title=Smash \u2013 Season 1|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 2, 2012}}</ref> Maureen Ryan of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' called it one of the strongest new shows of the season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan |first=Maureen |url=http://www.aoltv.com/2011/11/21/smash-nbc-exclusive-first-look-katharine-mcphee/ |title='Smash' Exclusive First Look: Is This the Show That Will Save NBC? |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=November 21, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> ''The Huffington Post'' writer Karen Ocamb praised the writing and the creativity of the series.<ref name=\"huffington\">{{cite web|last=Ocamb |first=Karen |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/karen-ocamb/nbc-smash_b_1206829.html |title=Karen Ocamb: NBC's Smash Is a Musical About Creativity and the Drama of Big Dreams |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=January 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> Mary McNamara of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the show a \"triumph\" and also went on to say that the creator Theresa Rebeck as well as her team, \"have managed to capture the grand and sweeping gesture that is musical theater and inject it with the immediate intimacy of television.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=McNamara |first=Mary |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-smash-review-20120206,0,1017618.story |title=Television review: 'Smash' on NBC NBC's new series featuring Debra Messing and 'American Idol' runner-up Katharine McPhee lovingly examines Broadway's travails and triumphs |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=February 6, 2012 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> [[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the program a rave review: \"[It's so] good you can't help wondering why no one thought of it before, a compelling mix of credible real-life melodrama with a fictionalized approximation of what it takes to get a Broadway show from the idea stage to opening night.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=David Wiegand |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2012/01/31/DDH91N0FKL.DTL |title='Smash' review: NBC series lives up to title |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=February 1, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> Tim Goodman from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called the pilot episode \"Excellent, a bar-raiser for broadcast networks\", and superior to ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''.<ref name=\"thr\">{{cite web|last=Goodman |first=Tim |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/smash-tv-review-katharine-mcphee-debra-messing-286296 |title=Smash: TV Review |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 2, 2012 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> He also praised writing and acting for the series, comparing it to the quality of a [[Cable television|cable television series]].<ref name=\"thr\"/> Matt Mitovich of [[TVLine]] called the cast \"pretty damn perfect\" and complimented the musical numbers.<ref name=\"tvline\">{{cite web|author=Mitovich, Matt |url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/12/tv-review-smash-nbc/ |title=Winter TV First Impression: Does NBC's Smash Hit All the Right Notes? |publisher=[[TVLine]] |date=December 29, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> Robert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the show three and a half out of four stars and wrote, \"Unless you're allergic to musicals in general and Broadway in particular, you should find that a compelling central story, a strong cast, an out-of-the-procedural-mold premise and some rousing, roof-raising numbers more than compensate for any lingering problems.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/story/2012-02-05/NBCs-Smash-review/52974100/1 |title='Smash' pulls out all the entertainment stops and succeeds |work=[[USA Today]] |date=February 6, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |last=Bianco |first=Robert}}</ref> Tanner Stransky of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' ranked the pilot episode as the 8th best television episode of 2012 saying, \"After we watched the subsequent 14 episodes of ''Smash'' with a mixture of fascination and dismay (seriously, did Debra Messing's Julia wear a men's pajama top to meet her lover?), it was difficult to recall that the pilot was positively magical. But it was. In fact, that episode-ending performance of 'Let Me Be Your Star' (featuring dueling divas Megan Hilty and Katharine McPhee) was among TV's most watchable and gleeful three minutes of the year. Rare is the series whose high-water mark is its pilot, and Smash is a shining example.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/12/31/best-and-worst-tv-episodes-2012/ |title=Best & Worst of 2012: 10 great and 5 not-so-great episodes |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 31, 2012 |accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nChris Harnick of ''The Huffington Post'' wrote, \"How has the rest of Season 1 been so far? Not so phenomenal. That's not to say it has been downright terrible\u2014there have been some highly entertaining moments\u2014but it certainly hasn't been goosebumps-inducing, like the final moments of Episode 1, set to '[[Let Me Be Your Star]].'\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/chris-harnick/smash-season-2-nbc_b_1375703.html |title='Smash': Season 2 Can Win Me Back If... |newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]] |last=Harnick |first=Chris |date=March 26, 2012 |accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref> Kevin Fallon summed up the response in ''[[The Atlantic]]'', writing that \"there's been an almost visceral reaction to how rapidly and sharply the show's quality has dipped, and just how much promise ''Smash'' has thwarted...In other words: It's ''bad.''\" Fallon cites other critics in demonstrating the general acceptance of this opinion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/04/the-tv-musical-is-dead/255643/ |title=The TV Musical is Dead |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=April 10, 2012 |accessdate=April 10, 2012 |last=Fallon |first=Kevin}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n''Smash'' received a number of awards and nominations. In 2012, it was nominated for four [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, winning one for Choreography.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"width:95%;\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:23%;\"| Award\n! style=\"width:35%;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:25px;\"| Recipient\n! style=\"width:8%;\"| Result\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2011\n| [[1st Critics' Choice Television Awards|Critics' Choice Television Award]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Most Exciting New Series|Most Exciting New Series]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2012\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/emmys.com/files/EmmyNoms64-Press-Release-6.pdf |work=[[Emmys.com]] |title=2012 Emmy Nominations Press Release |page=7 |accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/emmys.com/files/2012-Creative-Arts-Emmys-Press-Release.pdf |work=Emmys.com |title=2012 Creative Arts Emmy Winners Press Release |accessdate=March 30, 2013 |page=20 |date=September 15, 2012}}</ref>\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]]\n| [[Uma Thurman]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Choreography|Outstanding Choreography]]\n| Josh Bergasse\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 