"|Italy  \n||Division||Europe ('''except United Kingdom, Ireland''')\n|-  \n|[[Maserati]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Italy   \n||Subsidiary||Global  \n|-  \n|[[RAM Trucks|RAM]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|United States  \n||Division||North America, Brazil, Middle East, Peru, Australia\n|- style=\"background:gainsboro;\"  \n|colspan=\"5\"|<big>'''9. [[Renault]]'''</big> (France)\n|-\n|[[Alpine (automobile)|Alpine]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|France\n||Subsidiary||Europe, Japan and Australia\n|-\n|[[Automobile Dacia|Dacia]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Romania]]\n||Subsidiary||Europe, North Africa\n|-\n|[[AvtoVAZ|Lada]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Russia\n||Business unit||Russia, Belarus, Ukraine, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Austria, France, Germany, Hungary, Egypt\n|- \n||[[Renault]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|France  \n||Division||Global ('''except USA, Canada, Pakistan, The Philippines''')\n|- \n|[[Renault Samsung Motors]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|South Korea  \n||Subsidiary||South Korea\n|-\n|- style=\"background:gainsboro;\"  \n|colspan=\"5\"|<big>'''10. [[Groupe PSA]]'''</big> (France)  \n|-\n|[[Citro\u00ebn]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|France  \n||Division||Europe, Central and South America, Northern and Western Africa, South Africa, Madagascar, Australia, New Zealand, Asia ('''except USA, Canada, India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Thailand, Indonesia''')\n|-\n|[[DS Automobiles|DS]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|France\n||Division||Europe and China\n|-  \n|[[Peugeot]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|France  \n||Division||Global ('''except USA, Canada, India, Pakistan''')\n|-\n|[[Opel]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Germany\n||Subsidiary||Europe ('''except United Kingdom'''), North Africa, South Africa, Middle East, Singapore, Mongolia, Chile\n|-\n|[[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|United Kingdom\n||Subsidiary||United Kingdom\n|}\n* General Motors India stopped producing vehicles for the Indian market in 2017. It however continues to export vehicles to other markets.\n\n==See also==\n\n{{div col}}\n* [[Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers]]\n* [[Automotive industry by country]]\n* [[Automotive industry crisis of 2008\u20132010]]\n* [[Automotive industry in the United States]]\n* [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)]]\n* [[Effects of the 2008\u201310 automotive industry crisis on the United States]]\n* [[List of countries by motor vehicle production]]\n* [[Motocycle]]\n* [[List of largest automotive companies by revenue]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Prone to spam|date=September 2015}}\n{{Z148}}<!--     {{No more links}}\n\n       Please be cautious adding more external links.\n\nWikipedia is not a collection of links and should not be used for advertising.\n\n     Excessive or inappropriate links will be removed.\n\n See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.\n\nIf there are already suitable links, propose additions or replacements on\nthe article's talk page, or submit your link to the relevant category at\nDMOZ (dmoz.org) and link there using {{Dmoz}}.\n\n-->\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Automotive industry}}\n* [https://autoalliance.org/ Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers]\n* [https://informaticguru.com/automobile news/ ]\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Cars|Trains|Transport|Business and economics|Companies}}\n{{Automotive industry}}\n{{Industries}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Automotive Industry}}\n[[Category:Automotive industry| ]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Mass production]]\n[[Category:Heavy industry]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Organizations involved with motor vehicles}}\n[[File:Geely assembly line in Beilun, Ningbo.JPG|thumb|A modern assembly-line]]\n[[File:\u0160koda cars being transported by rail at Kutn\u00e1 Hora m\u011bsto train station, Czech Republic - 20140710.ogv|thumb|A video showing new [[SEAT]], [[w:\u0160koda Auto|\u0160koda]] & [[w:Volkswagen|Volkswagen]] cars being transported by rail at {{w|Kutn\u00e1 Hora}} m\u011bsto train station in the Czech Republic]]\nThe '''automotive industry''' comprises a wide range of [[company|companies]] and [[organization]]s involved in the [[design]], [[Business development|development]], [[manufacturing]], [[marketing]], and [[selling]] of [[motor vehicle]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Britannica|45050|Automotive industry}}</ref> It is one of the world's largest [[Economic sector|economic sectors]] by [[revenue]]. The automotive industry does not include industries dedicated to the [[Service (motor vehicle)|maintenance]] of [[Car|automobiles]] following delivery to the end-user,{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} such as [[Automobile repair shop|automobile repair shops]] and [[motor fuel]] [[filling station]]s.\n\nThe word ''automotive'' comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''autos'' (self), and [[Latin]] ''motivus'' (of [[motion]]), referring to any form of self-powered vehicle.{{clarify | reason = Submarines? Airships?|date=May 2019}} This term, as proposed by [[Elmer Ambrose Sperry|Elmer Sperry]]<ref name=\"STS of US\">\n{{cite book\n |title= Scientific and Technical Societies of the United States\n |year= 1968 |publisher= National Academy of Sciences\n |location= Washington DC |page= 164\n |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pS8rAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA164&lpg=PA164&dq=%22Society+of+Automobile+Engineers%22+-inauthor:%22Society+of+Automotive+Engineers%22&source=bl&ots=GPYxVdf2Gv&sig=-Qiz_agHsvXxF4LkOAtNS_b8YJ8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YB0YUMHdLcPV0QHIuoHAAg&ved=0CGEQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Society%20of%20Automobile%20Engineers%20-inauthor%3A%22Society%20of%20Automotive%20Engineers%22&f=false\n |edition= Eighth |accessdate= 25 March 2014\n}}\n</ref>{{qn|date=October 2018}}\n(1860-1930), first came into use with reference to automobiles in 1898.<ref>\n{{OEtymD|automotive|accessdate= 2018-10-16}}\n</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of the automobile}}\n[[File:Thomas B Jeffery Works Drawing.jpg|thumb|[[Thomas B. Jeffery Company|Thomas B. Jeffery]] automobile factory in Kenosha, Wisconsin, c.1916]]\n[[File:Workers in Fiat factories, Turin.jpg|thumb|[[Fiat]] assembly line in 1961]]\n\nThe automotive industry began in the [[1860s]] with hundreds of manufacturers that pioneered the [[Brass Era car|horseless carriage]]. For many decades, the [[United States]] led the world in total automobile production. In 1929, before the [[Great Depression]], the world had 32,028,500 automobiles in use, and the U.S. automobile industry produced over 90% of them. At that time the U.S. had one car per 4.87 persons.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FSgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA84&dq=U.S.+makes+ninety+percent+of+world's+automobiles |title=U.S. Makes Ninety Percent of World's Automobiles |journal=Popular Science |date=November 1929 |page=84 |volume=115 |issue=5 |accessdate=6 August 2013 }}</ref> After [[World War II]], the U.S. produced about 75 percent of world's auto production. In 1980, the U.S. was overtaken by [[Japan]] and then became world's leader again in 1994. In 2006, Japan narrowly passed the U.S. in production and held this rank until 2009, when [[China]] took the top spot with 13.8 million units. With 19.3 million units manufactured in 2012, China almost doubled the U.S. production, with 10.3 million units, while Japan was in third place with 9.9 million units.<ref name=\"Production Statistics\">{{cite web|publisher=OICA |url= http://oica.net/category/production-statistics/ |title=2012 Production Statistics |accessdate=6 August 2013 }}</ref> From 1970 (140 models) over 1998 (260 models) to 2012 (684 models), the number of automobile models in the U.S. has grown exponentially.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Aichner|first1=T.|last2=Coletti|first2= P|date=2013|title=Customers' online shopping preferences in mass customization|journal=Journal of Direct, Data and Digital Marketing Practice|volume=15|issue=1|pages=20\u201335}}</ref>\n\n==Safety==\n{{Main|Automobile safety}}\nSafety is a state that implies to be protected from any risk, danger, damage or cause of injury. In the automotive industry, safety means that users, operators or [[manufacturers]] do not face any risk or danger coming from the motor vehicle or its spare parts. Safety for the automobiles themselves, implies that there is no risk of damage.\n\nSafety in the automotive industry is particularly important and therefore highly regulated. [[Automobiles]] and other [[motor vehicles]] have to comply with a certain number of norms and regulations, whether local or international, in order to be accepted on the market. The standard [[ISO 26262]], is considered as one of the best practice framework for achieving automotive [[functional safety]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.iso.org/iso/home/store/catalogue_tc/catalogue_detail.htm?csnumber=54591 |title= ISO 26262-10:2012 Road vehicles -- Functional safety -- Part 10: Guideline on ISO 26262 |publisher=International Organization for Standardization |accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn case of safety issues, danger, [[product defect]] or faulty procedure during the manufacturing of the motor vehicle, the maker can request to return either a batch or the entire production run. This procedure is called [[product recall]]. Product recalls happen in every industry and can be production-related or stem from the raw material.\n\nProduct and operation tests and inspections at different stages of the [[value chain]] are made to avoid these product recalls by ensuring end-user security and safety and compliance with the automotive industry requirements. However, the automotive industry is still particularly concerned about product recalls, which cause considerable financial consequences.\n\n==Economy==\n{{See also|Automotive industry by country}}\nAround the world, there were about 806 million cars and light trucks on the road in 2007, consuming over {{convert|980|e9litres|m3}} of [[gasoline]] and [[diesel fuel]] yearly.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Plunkett Research |url=http://www.plunkettresearch.com/Industries/AutomobilesTrucks/AutomobileTrends/tabid/89/Default.aspx |title=Automobile Industry Introduction |year=2008 |accessdate=25 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219120341/http://plunkettresearch.com/Industries/AutomobilesTrucks/AutomobileTrends/tabid/89/Default.aspx |archivedate=19 December 2010 }}</ref> The automobile is a primary mode of [[Transport|transportation]] for many developed economies. The Detroit branch of [[Boston Consulting Group]] predicted that, by 2014, one-third of world demand would be in the four [[BRIC]] markets (Brazil, Russia, India and China). Meanwhile, in the developed countries, the automotive industry has slowed down.<ref name=\"twnside1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.twnside.org.sg/title2/gtrends/gtrends396.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013151102/http://www.twnside.org.sg/title2/gtrends/gtrends396.htm|first=Martin|last=Khor|title=Developing economies slowing down|archivedate=13 October 2012|work=twnside.org.sg|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref> It is also expected that this trend will continue, especially as the younger generations of people (in highly urbanized countries) no longer want to own a car anymore, and prefer other modes of transport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/global/Documents/Manufacturing/gx-global-automotive-consumer-study-europe-final.pdf |format=PDF |title=2014 Global Automotive Consumer Study : Exploring consumer preferences and mobility choices in Europe |publisher=Deloittelcom |accessdate=2015-07-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704135550/http://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/global/Documents/Manufacturing/gx-global-automotive-consumer-study-europe-final.pdf |archivedate=2015-07-04 }}</ref> Other potentially powerful automotive markets are [[Iran]] and [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul A.|last=Eisenstein|url=http://www.thedetroitbureau.com/2010/01/building-brics-the-four-markets-that-could-soon-dominate-the-automotive-world/|title=Building BRIC's: 4 Markets Could Soon Dominate the Auto World|website=TheDetroitBureau.com}}</ref>\nEmerging auto markets already buy more cars than established markets. According to a J.D. Power study, emerging markets accounted for 51 percent of the global [[Light commercial vehicle|light-vehicle]] sales in 2010. The study, performed in 2010 expected this trend to accelerate.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Truth About Cars|author=Bertel Schmitt|url=https://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2011/02/auto-industry-sets-new-world-record-in-2010-will-do-it-again-in-2011 |title=Auto Industry Sets New World Record In 2010. Will Do It Again In 2011|date=15 February 2011|accessdate=2019-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=J.D. Power and Associates|url=http://businesscenter.jdpower.com/news/pressrelease.aspx?ID=2011018|title=Global Automotive Outlook for 2011 Appears Positive as Mature Auto Markets Recover, Emerging Markets Continue to Expand|date=15 February 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217022100/http://businesscenter.jdpower.com/news/pressrelease.aspx?ID=2011018|archive-date=17 February 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, more recent reports (2012) confirmed the opposite; namely that the automotive industry was slowing down even in BRIC countries.<ref name=\"twnside1\"/> In the United States, vehicle sales peaked in 2000, at 17.8 million units.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecherrycreeknews.com/u-s-vehicle-sales-peaked-in-2005/ |title=U.S. vehicle sales peaked in 2000 |publisher=thecherrycreeknews.com |date=2015-05-27 |accessdate=2015-06-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528010752/http://www.thecherrycreeknews.com/u-s-vehicle-sales-peaked-in-2005/ |archive-date=28 May 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==World motor vehicle production==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 350\n| header = World Motor Vehicle Production<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bts.gov/bts/archive/publications/national_transportation_statistics/table_01_23 |title=Table 1-23: World Motor Vehicle Production, Selected Countries (Thousands of vehicles) |publisher=[[Bureau of Transportation Statistics]] |date= May 23, 2017|accessdate=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n| header_align = center\n| image1 = Motor_Vehicle_Prod_volume_RITA_T1-23.svg\n| caption1 = <center>Production volume (1000 vehicles)</center>\n1960s: Post war increase\n\n1970s: [[1970s energy crisis|Oil]] crisis and tighter safety and emission regulation.\n\n1990s: production started in [[Newly industrialized country|NICs]]\n\n2000s: rise of China as top producer\n\n[[Automotive industry crisis of 2008\u20132010]]\n| image2 = Motor_Vehicle_Prod_share_RITA_T1-23.svg\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 = '''to 1950''': USA had produced more than 80% of motor vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hydrogenambassadors.com/meet-aae/whec15/17.php |title=Arno A. Evers FAIR-PR |publisher=Hydrogenambassadors.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n'''1950s''': UK, Germany and France restarted production.\n\n'''1960s''': Japan started production and increased volume through the 1980s.\nUS, Japan, Germany, France and UK produced about 80% of motor vehicles through the 1980s.\n\n'''1990s''': Korea became a volume producer. In 2004, Korea became No. 5 passing France.\n\n'''2000s''': China increased its production drastically, and became the world's largest producing country in 2009 .\n\n'''2010s''': India overtakes Korea, Canada, Spain to become 5th largest automobile  producer.\n\n'''2013''': The share of China (25.4%), India, Korea,  Brazil and Mexico rose to 43%, while the share of USA (12.7%), Japan, Germany, France and UK  fell to 34%.\n\n'''2018''': India overtakes Germany to become 4th largest automobile producer.\n}}\n\n[[File:World motor production (1997-2016).png|thumb|707x707px|World motor production (1997-2016)]]\n\n===By year===\n{{See also|List of countries by motor vehicle production}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"48\" | Year\n! width=\"67\" | Production\n! width=\"52\" | Change\n! width=\"70\" | Source\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 1997\n| 54,434,000\n| \u2014\n| <ref name= \"OICA9798\">{{cite web|website=oica.net|url=http://oica.net/wp-content/uploads/2007/06/cl98type.pdf|title=1998 - 1997 WORLD MOTOR VEHICLE PRODUCTION BY TYPE AND ECONOMIC AREA|accessdate=21 July 2015|format=pdf}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 1998\n| 52,987,000\n| {{decrease}} 2.7%\n| <ref name= \"OICA9798\"/>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 1999\n| 56,258,892\n| {{increase}} 6.2%\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=1999 Production Statistics|website=oica.net|url=http://oica.net/category/production-statistics/1999-statistics/}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 2000\n| 58,374,162\n| {{increase}} 3.8%\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2000 Production Statistics|website=oica.net|url=http://oica.net/category/production-statistics/2000-statistics/}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 2001\n| 56,304,925\n| {{decrease}} 3.5%\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2001 Production Statistics|website=oica.net|url=http://oica.net/category/production-statistics/2001-statistics/}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 2002\n| 58,994,318\n| {{increase}} 4.8%\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2002 Production Statistics|website=oica.net|url=http://oica.net/category/production-statistics/2002-statistics/}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 2003\n| 60,663,225\n| {{increase}} 2.8%\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2003 Production Statistics|website=oica.net|url=http://oica.net/category/production-statistics/2003-statistics/}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| 2004\n| 64,496,220\n| {{increase}} 6.3%\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2004 Production Statistics|website=oica.net|url=h