 2011-06-19\n| quote       =\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"blokken\">{{cite news\n |title       = Blokken\n |url         = http://www.image-line.com/documents/blokken.html\n |publisher   = Image-Line\n |accessdate  = 2011-06-19\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110725141651/http://www.image-line.com/documents/blokken.html\n |archivedate = 2011-07-25\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"maximus\">{{cite news\n| title       = Maximus\n| url         = http://www.image-line.com/documents/maximus.html\n| publisher   = Image-Line\n| accessdate  = 2011-06-19\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"awardsez\">{{cite news\n |title       = EZGenerator Award Gallery\n |url         = http://www.ezgenerator.com/documents/awards.html\n |publisher   = Image-Line\n |accessdate  = 2011-06-19\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110725123421/http://www.ezgenerator.com/documents/awards.html\n |archivedate = 2011-07-25\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"team\">{{cite news\n| title       = Our Team\n| url         = http://www.image-line.com/documents/team.html\n| publisher   = Image-Line\n| date        =\n| accessdate  = 2011-06-19\n| quote       =\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n=== Other references ===\n* <!--<ref name=\"somestaff\">-->{{cite news\n| title       = FL Studio Features\n| url         = http://www.loopking.com/FruityLoops_soundkits.php\n| publisher   = LoopKing\n| accessdate  = 2011-06-19\n}}<!--</ref>-->\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.image-line.com/}}\n*[http://www.flstudio.com FL Studio website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20020921205305/http://deckadance.com/ Deckadance website]\n*[http://www.ezgenerator.com/ EZGenerator website]\n\n[[Category:Software companies of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Companies based in East Flanders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name =Image-Line\n| logo = [[File:ImageLineLogo.png|240px]]\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1994}}<ref name=\"Image-Line Company Page\">{{cite web|title=Image-Line Company Page|url=http://www.image-line.com/company/|website=www.image-line.com/|publisher=Image Line|accessdate=22 September 2014}}</ref><br>[[Belgium]]\n| location =  [[Ghent]]\n| key_people = Jean-Marie Cannie<br/><small>(Founder, [[Chief technology officer|CTO]]) </small><br/>Frank Van Biesen<br/><small>(Founder, [[Chief operating officer|COO]])</small><ref name=\"team\"/>\n| industry = [[Software]]\n| products = [[FL Studio]] / [[FL Studio Mobile]]<br/>[[Deckadance]]<br/>[[EZGenerator]]\n| revenue =\n| num_employees =\n| parent =\n| homepage = [http://www.image-line.com image-line.com]\n}}\n'''Image-Line Software''' (commonly known as simply '''Image-Line''') is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[software]] company best known for its [[digital audio workstation]] program [[FL Studio]]<ref name=\"musik\"/> and related [[audio plugin|audio plugins]] such as [[Sytrus]]<ref name=\"sytrus\"/> and [[Harmor]].<ref name=\"Harmor\"/> Image-Line was founded in 1994.<ref name=\"Image-Line Company Page\"/> In 2007, Image-Line introduced [[Deckadance]], a virtual DJ console application.<ref name=\"musik\"/> The company also produced [[EZGenerator]], a template-based [[web development|web editing]] program.<ref name=\"awardsez\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early development===\nImage-Line was founded by Jean-Marie Cannie and Frank Van Biesen, who after seven years of creating [[stock market]] software for Pavell Software, decided in 1992 to branch into [[video games]]. Their first product was an [[adult video game]] of ''[[Tetris]]'', which they then offered on [[floppy disks]] in the ad section of ''Computer Magazine''. Around this time [[CD-ROM]] games such as [[The 7th Guest]] were becoming popular, inspiring Van Biesen and Cannie to begin working with Private, one of the larger producers of adult video games at the time. Private released multiple Image-Line CD-ROM games including ''Private Prison'' and ''Private Castle''.<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/><ref name=\"interview\"/> The company officially adopted the name Image-Line in 1994.<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/>\n\n===Didier \"Gol\" Dambrin===\nAround the time they released the games for Private, [[IBM]] launched the \"Da Vinci\" contest where the first prizes were color laptops. Image-Line, which at the time had little money, won the contest in the multimedia category after reworking one of their game environments to fit the contest criteria.<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/><ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nImage-Line took an interest in Didier \"Gol\" Dambrin, the developer who won the overall Da Vinci contest as well as the Game category. They hired the 19-year-old to work for them, and his first game for the company was the game ''Private Investigator.'' <ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/><ref name=\"interview\"/> Dambrin's next project for Image-Line was the platform game ''Eat This'',<ref name=\"eat this\"/>  a [[shoot 'em up]] game that involved killing aliens.<ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nOther Image-Line developers created products such as the [[invoice|invoicing]] program Fact2000 and E-OfficeDirect, a content-based web tool that would a precursor to their later product [[EZGenerator]].<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/> Image-Line also topped the Belgian game charts 4 years in a row with their CD version of the Belgian TV [[game show]] ''[[Blokken]].''<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/><ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\n===Audio software===\nIn 1997 Dambrin gained an interest in music applications of the time such as Hammerhead and Rebirth 338, and developed a simple [[MIDI]]-only [[drum machine]] in an effort to merge the two products into a [[step sequencer]] that utilized both rows and steps. Dubbed FruityLoops 1.0, the program didn't fit with Image-Line's other product lines of the time. However, the demo version released in December 1997 became so popular that the number of downloads quickly overwhelmed the Image-Line servers.<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/> To gather income to support their servers, Image-Line had Dambrin develop an [[EJay]] clone called FruityTracks. Image-Line then served as the program's [[OEM]] for [[Mattel]]. The program was released as Pro-DJ in [[France]] and the [[UK]], and Radio 538 Music Machine in The [[Netherlands]] and [[Belgium]].<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/>\n\nImage-Line continued to develop the FruityLoops application from a simple [[drum machine]] into a large and complex [[digital audio workstation]]. FruityLoops was eventually renamed [[FL Studio]] for branding purposes and to avoid a prolonged trademark dispute in the [[United States]] with [[Kelloggs]].<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/> FL Studio is now one of the most popular software production systems in the world, and Image-Line's flagship program.<ref name=\"musik\"/> A multitude of [[plug-in (computing)|plug-in]]s have been developed by Image-Line to work with FL Studio, including [[synthesizers]] such as [[Sytrus]] and [[Audio signal processing|effects]] [[plugins]] such as Maximus and Edison.<ref name=\"musik\"/> In 2007 Image-Line released [[Deckadance]], a [[DJ]] [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]] program developed by programmer [[Arguru]]. Deckadance works as both a stand-alone program and as a FL Studio plugin.\n\n===Other software===\nBeyond audio products, Image-Line developed and distributed [[EZGenerator]], a software program for website design and maintenance. EZGenerator has won multiple awards since its release.<ref name=\"awardsez\"/>\n\n==Products==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! Software\n! Release\n! Notes\n|-\n\n|[[FL Studio]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\u2013present\n|Image-Line's flagship [[digital audio workstation]]. The most recent major version is FL Studio 20, released on May 22, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/fl-studio-20-released-with-multiple-new-features-and-full-mac-compatibility|title=FL Studio 20 released with multiple new features and full Mac compatibility|work=|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[FL Studio Mobile]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2011\u2013present\n|Released June 21, 2011, a version of FL Studio for [[iOS (Apple)|iOS]]<ref name=\"what\"/> and on April 17, 2013 for Android\n|-\n|[[Deckadance]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\u20132015\n|A DJ console and mixing tool, similar to [[Scratch LIVE]] and [[Traktor]]. Version 2.43 is the most recent release from Image-Line.<ref name=\"deckadance\"/> Deckadance was sold to Stanton/Gibson in 2015. Their latest release is Deckadance 2.72<ref name=\"stanton\"/>\n|-\n\n|[[EZGenerator]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\u20132017\n|A template-based [[web development|web editing]] program, and a natural progression of their earlier E-OfficeDirect program, EZGenerator has won numerous software awards.<ref name=\"awardsez\"/> No longer sold.\n|-\n\n|Fact2000\n| style=\"text-align:center;|1997-2012\n|An [[invoice|invoicing]] and [[contact management]] program. No longer sold.\n|-\n\n|FruityTracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1999-2000\n|A track mixing program. No longer sold (was integrated into FL Studio).\n|-\n\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! Video Games\n! Release\n! Notes\n|-\n|''Porntris''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1992\n|An [[Adult video game|erotic]] version of the popular ''[[Tetris]]'' game.<ref name=\"kvr\"/><ref name=\"porntris\"/>\n|-\n|''Private Investigator''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1996\n|Awarded [[1996 in video gaming|1996]] Best Interactive Game at the AMEE Award Show in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"sec\"/>\n|-\n|''Eat This''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\n|A side-scrolling [[Shoot 'em up|\"run and gun\" shooter]] computer game that involves killing aliens with machine guns. While the original release was 2-D, the later version had 30 minutes of 3D animated video.<ref name=\"eat this\"/>\n|-\n|''Blokken''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998-2001\n|A [[CD-ROM]] equivalent to the [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[quiz show]] released in [[Belgium]]. The game topped the Belgian game charts 4 years in a row,<ref name=\"blokken\"/> and was released in four versions. It has sold over 50,000 copies.<ref name=\"imagelinehistory\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! Virtual Effects\n! Release\n! Notes\n|-\n\n|Gross Beat\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|A time-, pitch-, and volume-manipulation effect.\n|-\n\n|Maximus\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| Maximus is a multi-band audio limiter and compressor for mastering projects or tracks. It also serves as a [[noise gate]], expander, ducker, and [[de-esser]],<ref name=\"maximus\"/>\n|-\n\n|Hardcore\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|A multi-effects suite of plugins designed to resemble guitarists' [[stompbox]]es.<ref name=\"editions\"/>\n|-\n\n|Juice Pack\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|A collection of Image-Line proprietary plugins ported to [[Virtual Studio Technology|VST]] format for use in other music hosts. The contents of this pack has changed since its release; at the time of this writing it includes the Delay, Delay Bank, EQUO, Flangus, LovePhilter, Multiband Compressor, Notebook, Parametric EQ, Parametric EQ 2, Spectroman, Stereo Enhancer, Vocoder, Wave Candy, and Wave Shaper plugins.\n|-\n\n|Edison\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\u2013present<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|A wave editor in VST format that also function as a standalone program.\n|-\n|Pitcher\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|A real time pitch correction filter - similar to Antares Autotune.\n|-\n|NewTone\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|A piano roll pitch correction effect - similar to Melodyne.\n|-\n|Vocodex\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2009\u2013present<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|A digital [[vocoder]] developed by Didier Dambrin.<ref name=\"editions\"/>\n|-\n|Fruity Stereo Shaper\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2009\u2013present\n|A stereo processor with a mixer for left/right channels and their inverted equivalents, and controls for channel delay and phase offset.<ref name=\"editions\"/>\n|-\n\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! Virtual Instruments\n! Release\n! Notes\n|-\n\n|[[Sytrus]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\u2013present<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|A hybrid, semi-modular synthesizer combining subtractive, additive, and FM synthesis.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|-\n\n|DirectWave\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2005\u2013present<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|A [[software sampler]] that provides sample recording, waveform editing, and DSP effects.<ref name=\"editions\"/>\n|-\n\n|SliceX\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008\u2013present<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|A beat-slicing sampler for processing and re-arranging recorded drumloops.\n|-\n\n|Harmless\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2009\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|title=Image Line releases Harmless - Additive Subtractive Synthesizer|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/news/image_line_releases_harmless_additive_subtractive_synthesizer_13291|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio|accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref> \n|Simplified additive synthesizer with a unique signal chain.<ref name=\"deckaplugins\"/>\n|-\n\n|[[Harmor]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2011\u2013present\n|Advanced Version of Harmless along with waveform views, envelopes, LFOs, and modulation mappings from Sytrus.<ref name=\"Harmor\">{{cite web|title=Image Line - Harmor|url=http://www.image-line.com/documents/harmor.html|publisher=Image Line|accessdate=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n\n|Toxic Biohazard\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|A virtual FM synthesizer similar to Sytrus.\n|-\n\n|Sawer\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|A vintage-modeling synthesizer; Sawer attempts to emulate old [[Soviet Union]]-era subtractive synthesizers.\n|-\n\n|Morphine\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|An easy-to-program additive synthesizer.<ref name=\"deckaplugins\"/>\n|-\n\n|PoiZone\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|An easy-to-program subtractive synthesizer.<ref name=\"deckaplugins\"/>\n|-\n\n|Ogun/Autogun\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2009\u2013present<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|Ogun is An advanced additive synthesizer specialized in creating metallic timbres, while Autogun - A free version of Ogun limited to semi-random preset generation.<ref name=\"deckaplugins\"/>\n|-\n\n|Sakura\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2009\u2013present<ref name=\"history\"/>\n|A physical-modeling synthesizer designed to emulate [[string instrument]]s.\n|-\n\n|Drumaxx\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\u2013present\n|Percussion synthesizer.<ref name=\"fetures\"/>\n|-\n\n|Groove Machine\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2011\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|title=Image Line releases version 1.0.2 of Groove Machine|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/news/image-line-releases-version-1-0-2-of-groove-machine-17651|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> \n|[[Step sequencer]] with the ability to automate all parameters per-step.<ref>{{cite web|title=Groove Machine by Image Line|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/product/groove-machine-by-image-line/details|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n\n|Wasp/Wasp XT\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|title=Image Line Wasp 2 VSTi released|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/news/image_line_wasp_2_vsti_released_71|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio}}</ref> \n|A \"broad\" [[Analogue synthesizer|analogue]] emulation synthesizer, intended to emulate analogue synthesizers in general.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wasp|url=http://www.image-line.com/plugins/Synths/WASP/|work=Image-Line|publisher=Image Line}}</ref> \n|-\n\n|SimSynth Live\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|title=Image Line SimSynth Live VSTi & DXi released|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/news/image_line_simsynth_live_vsti_and_dxi_released_388|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio}}</ref>\n|Three oscillator synthesizer with [[Oberheim]]-inspired SVF filter.<ref>{{cite web|title=SimSynth Live by Image Line|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/product/simsynth_live_by_image_line/details|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio}}</ref> \n|-\n\n|DX10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|title=PluginSpot/Image Line DX10 Released|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/news/pluginspot_image_line_dx10_released_136|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio}}</ref> \n|[[Frequency Modulation Synthesis|FM Synthesizer]] that features low CPU usage.<ref>{{cite web|title=DX10 by Image Line|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/product/dx10_by_image_line/details|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio}}</ref> \n|-\n\n|DrumSynth Live\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|title=Image Line releases DrumSynth Live VSTi|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/news/image_line_releases_drumsynth_live_vsti_7735|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio}}</ref> \n|Drum synthesizer based on two noise generators run through band pass filters.  VSTi version of the standalone program by Maxim Digital Audio.<ref>{{cite web|title=DrumSynth Live by Image Line|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/product/drumsynth_live_by_image_line/details|work=KVR Audio|publisher=KVR Audio}}</ref> \n|-\n\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[FL Studio]]\n*[[FL Studio Mobile]]\n*[[Deckadance]]\n*[[EZGenerator]]\n*[[Sytrus]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"sec\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.secinfo.com/dSq2u.7211.htm\n|publisher=SEC Info\n|title=SEC Info - Private Media Group Inc - 424B3\n|accessdate = 2008-11-06}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"kvr\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.kvraudio.com/forum/archive/instruments/2004-04/40643.php\n|publisher=KVR Audio\n|title=KVR: Forum Archive - try the new sytrus\n|accessdate=2008-11-17\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212214335/http://www.kvraudio.com/forum/archive/instruments/2004-04/40643.php\n|archive-date=2012-02-12\n|u