{"title_page": "Shannon Airport (Virginia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Airport\n| name         = Shannon Airport\n| image        =\n| IATA         = EZF\n| ICAO         = KEZF\n| FAA          = EZF\n| type         = Public\n| owner-oper   = Private\n| city-served  = \n| location     = [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|38|15|58|N|077|26|57|W|region:US-VA_type:airport_scale:10000}}\n| elevation-f  =85\n| elevation-m  =26\n| website      = http://www.shannonezf.com/\n| pushpin_map            = USA Virginia#USA\n| pushpin_relief         = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Virginia / United States\n| pushpin_label          = '''EZF'''\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| r1-number    = 06/24\n| r1-length-f  = 2,999\n| r1-length-m  = 914\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number    = 15/33\n| r2-length-f  = 1300\n| r2-length-m  = 396\n| stat-year    =\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   =\n| footnotes    = Source:<ref name=AirNav>{{cite web|url=https://www.airnav.com/airport/KEZF|title=KEZF|accessdate=6 June 2019|publisher=AirNav}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Vultee V-1A Spcl NC16099 VA Avn Msm 21.04.04R edited-2.jpg|thumb|The Vultee V-1A at the [[Virginia Aviation Museum]] before its return to the Shannon Air Museum]]\n\n'''Shannon Airport''' {{Airport codes||KEZF|EZF}} is a public use airport located two miles south of the [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|City of Fredericksburg, Virginia]], [[United States]].<ref name=AirNav/> It was opened in October 1950 by Sidney L. Shannon Jr.<ref name=AOPA/>\n\n== Facilities and aircraft ==\nShannon Airport covers 62 acres<ref name=\"FAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=EZF&CFID=6009003&CFTOKEN=23859617|title=FAA Master Record for EZF, effective 23 May 2019|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=FAA}}</ref> adjacent to the [[American Civil War]] battlefield at [[Slaughter Pen Farm]].<ref name=AOPA>{{cite web|url=https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2018/february/pilot/shannons-rebirth|title=Shannon's rebirth|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=AOPA Pilot Magazine|date=February 2018}}</ref> There are 85 single-engine [[General aviation]] aircraft, 5 multi-engine aircraft, 2 helicopters, 2 [[Ultralight aircraft (United States)|ultralights]], and a single glider based on the field.<ref name=\"FAA\"/> The two runways, (grass, 15/33 and asphalt, 06/24), measure 1300' and 2999' respectively. The airport also has fuel service ([[Jet fuel|Jet A]] and [[100LL]]), courtesy cars, a restaurant, gift shop, and a flight school.<ref name=\"AirNav\"/><ref name=AOPA/>\n\n== Civil War history ==\nA major part of the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] was fought where the airport now stands.<ref name=AOPA/> A ditch at the end of what is now runway 24 became a key portion of the battle with hand-to-hand combat taking place before the Federal troops finally retreated.<ref name=AOPA/> Artillery was situated where the terminal is, and artifacts such as buttons, musket balls and artillery shells were found when the taxiway was replaced.<ref name=AOPA/> Many of these artifacts are currently on display at the Shannon Air Museum.<ref name=\"Shannon about\"/>\n\n== Air Museum ==\nShannon Airport is home to the Shannon Air Museum, founded in 1976. The museum currently displays the last surviving [[Vultee V-1]], along with other \"[[Golden Age of Aviation|Golden Age]]\" aircraft such as the [[Pitcairn Mailwing]], and [[Curtiss Robin]].<ref name=AOPA/><ref name=Shannon>{{cite web|url=http://www.shannonairmuseum.com/vultee-v1a|title=Shannon Air Museum|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=Shannon Air museum}}</ref><ref name=\"Shannon about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shannonairmuseum.com/about|title=Shannon Air museum about|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=Shannon Air Museum About page}}</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n*29 September 2012: A [[Cessna 150M]], registration number ''N66246'', went into a 90-degree left bank immediately after takeoff and descended in a spiral, striking the ground and killing the pilot and the single passenger. The accident was attributed to ''\"The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control during initial climb. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's [[Alcohol intoxication|impairment due to alcohol]].\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20120929X81653&AKey=1&RType=Final&IType=FA |title=NTSB Aviation Accident Final Report ERA12FA583 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|accessdate= 19 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 22 July 2013: A [[Cessna 172|Cessna 172M]], registration number ''N61954'', pitched down into a near-vertical full-power descent from an altitude of approximately {{convert|3000|ft|m|sigfig=1}} and struck the ground about {{convert|200|ft|m|sigfig=1}} northwest of the runway, killing the pilot and sole occupant. The pilot had recently been diagnosed with \"[[Major depressive disorder|severe recurrent major depression]],\" and after a brief altercation with him before the flight, his fianc\u00e9e had reported to local police that she believed he intended to kill himself. The accident was attributed to ''\"The pilot's intentional descent into the ground to commit [[suicide by pilot|suicide]].\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20130722X21859&AKey=1&RType=Final&IType=FA |title=NTSB Aviation Accident Final Report ERA13FA330 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|accessdate= 19 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 12 August 2016: A [[Beechcraft Baron#T-42A Cochise (95-B55B)|Beechcraft T-42A]], registration number ''N128VB'', struck the ground during an attempted [[go-around]] after an unsuccessful landing attempt, substantially damaging the aircraft and killing all 6 occupants. Investigators found no significant anomalies in the aircraft and its engines. The accident was attributed to ''\"The pilot(s) failure to maintain adequate airspeed during an attempted go-around, which resulted in an exceedance of the airplane's critical [[angle of attack]] and an [[stall (fluid dynamics)|aerodynamic stall]].\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20160812X50604&AKey=1&RType=Final&IType=FA |title=NTSB Aviation Accident Final Report ERA16FA288 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|accessdate= 18 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.shannonairmuseum.com/ Shannon Air Museum]\n[[Category:Airports in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Airport\n| name         = Shannon Airport\n| image        =\n| IATA         = EZF\n| ICAO         = KEZF\n| FAA          = EZF\n| type         = Public\n| owner-oper   = Private\n| city-served  = \n| location     = [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|38|15|58|N|077|26|57|W|region:US-VA_type:airport_scale:10000}}\n| elevation-f  =85\n| elevation-m  =26\n| website      = http://www.shannonezf.com/\n| pushpin_map            = USA Virginia#USA\n| pushpin_relief         = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Virginia / United States\n| pushpin_label          = '''EZF'''\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| r1-number    = 06/24\n| r1-length-f  = 2,999\n| r1-length-m  = 914\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number    = 15/33\n| r2-length-f  = 1300\n| r2-length-m  = 396\n| stat-year    =\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   =\n| footnotes    = Source:<ref name=AirNav>{{cite web|url=https://www.airnav.com/airport/KEZF|title=KEZF|accessdate=6 June 2019|publisher=AirNav}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Vultee V-1A Spcl NC16099 VA Avn Msm 21.04.04R edited-2.jpg|thumb|The Vultee V-1A at the [[Virginia Aviation Museum]] before its return to the Shannon Air Museum]]\n\n'''Shannon Airport''' {{Airport codes||KEZF|EZF}} is a public use airport located two miles south of the [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|City of Fredericksburg, Virginia]], [[United States]].<ref name=AirNav/> It was opened in October 1950 by Sidney L. Shannon Jr.<ref name=AOPA/>\n\n== Facilities and aircraft ==\nShannon Airport covers 62 acres<ref name=\"FAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=EZF&CFID=6009003&CFTOKEN=23859617|title=FAA Master Record for EZF, effective 23 May 2019|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=FAA}}</ref> adjacent to the [[American Civil War]] battlefield at [[Slaughter Pen Farm]].<ref name=AOPA>{{cite web|url=https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2018/february/pilot/shannons-rebirth|title=Shannon's rebirth|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=AOPA Pilot Magazine|date=February 2018}}</ref> There are 85 single-engine [[General aviation]] aircraft, 5 multi-engine aircraft, 2 helicopters, 2 [[Ultralight aircraft (United States)|ultralights]], and a single glider based on the field.<ref name=\"FAA\"/> The two runways, (grass, 15/33 and asphalt, 06/24), measure 1300' and 2999' respectively. The airport also has fuel service ([[Jet fuel|Jet A]] and [[100LL]]), courtesy cars, a restaurant, gift shop, and a flight school.<ref name=\"AirNav\"/><ref name=AOPA/>\n\n== Civil War history ==\nA major part of the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] was fought where the airport now stands.<ref name=AOPA/> A ditch at the end of what is now runway 06 became a key portion of the battle with hand-to-hand combat taking place before the Federal troops finally retreated.<ref name=AOPA/> Artillery was situated where the terminal is, and artifacts such as buttons, musket balls and artillery shells were found when the taxiway was replaced.<ref name=AOPA/> Many of these artifacts are currently on display at the Shannon Air Museum.<ref name=\"Shannon about\"/>\n\n== Air Museum ==\nShannon Airport is home to the Shannon Air Museum, founded in 1976. The museum currently displays the last surviving [[Vultee V-1]], along with other \"[[Golden Age of Aviation|Golden Age]]\" aircraft such as the [[Pitcairn Mailwing]], and [[Curtiss Robin]].<ref name=AOPA/><ref name=Shannon>{{cite web|url=http://www.shannonairmuseum.com/vultee-v1a|title=Shannon Air Museum|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=Shannon Air museum}}</ref><ref name=\"Shannon about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shannonairmuseum.com/about|title=Shannon Air museum about|accessdate=7 June 2019|publisher=Shannon Air Museum About page}}</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n*29 September 2012: A [[Cessna 150M]], registration number ''N66246'', went into a 90-degree left bank immediately after takeoff and descended in a spiral, striking the ground and killing the pilot and the single passenger. The accident was attributed to ''\"The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control during initial climb. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's [[Alcohol intoxication|impairment due to alcohol]].\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20120929X81653&AKey=1&RType=Final&IType=FA |title=NTSB Aviation Accident Final Report ERA12FA583 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|accessdate= 19 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 22 July 2013: A [[Cessna 172|Cessna 172M]], registration number ''N61954'', pitched down into a near-vertical full-power descent from an altitude of approximately {{convert|3000|ft|m|sigfig=1}} and struck the ground about {{convert|200|ft|m|sigfig=1}} northwest of the runway, killing the pilot and sole occupant. The pilot had recently been diagnosed with \"[[Major depressive disorder|severe recurrent major depression]],\" and after a brief altercation with him before the flight, his fianc\u00e9e had reported to local police that she believed he intended to kill himself. The accident was attributed to ''\"The pilot's intentional descent into the ground to commit [[suicide by pilot|suicide]].\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20130722X21859&AKey=1&RType=Final&IType=FA |title=NTSB Aviation Accident Final Report ERA13FA330 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|accessdate= 19 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 12 August 2016: A [[Beechcraft Baron#T-42A Cochise (95-B55B)|Beechcraft T-42A]], registration number ''N128VB'', struck the ground during an attempted [[go-around]] after an unsuccessful landing attempt, substantially damaging the aircraft and killing all 6 occupants. Investigators found no significant anomalies in the aircraft and its engines. The accident was attributed to ''\"The pilot(s) failure to maintain adequate airspeed during an attempted go-around, which resulted in an exceedance of the airplane's critical [[angle of attack]] and an [[stall (fluid dynamics)|aerodynamic stall]].\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20160812X50604&AKey=1&RType=Final&IType=FA |title=NTSB Aviation Accident Final Report ERA16FA288 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|accessdate= 18 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.shannonairmuseum.com/ Shannon Air Museum]\n[[Category:Airports in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Gorkypickeral", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCivil War history:End of 24", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_Airport_(Virginia)"}
